.TH "dolbybi" "1" "2018-04-03" "dolbybi 0.0+20180403" "Dolby B software decoder"
.hy
.SH NAME
.PP
dolbybi - Dolby B software decoder for digitised cassette tape
recordings
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
\f[B]dolbybi\f[R] \f[I]<infile.wav>\f[R] \f[I]<outfile.wav>\f[R]
[\f[I]options\f[R]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
\f[B]dolbybi\f[R] is a command-line program that decodes audio files
digitised from cassette tapes recorded in Dolby B.
It was written by Richard Evans between August 2014 and April 2016 as an
experimental program.
.PP
Dolby B noise reduction is normally built into a tape deck, where the
audio level fed into the decode circuits is approximately correct.
When using this program, the audio must have already been extracted and
digitised, so some trial and error is needed to find the correct level
(see \f[B]LEVEL ADJUSTMENT\f[R]).
.PP
Only WAV type 1 files are supported as input and output.
.SH OPTIONS
.SS Gain
.TP
\f[B]/IG\f[R]:\f[I]n\f[R]
Gain applied to the input file in dB (default: 0.0).
.TP
\f[B]/OG\f[R]:\f[I]n\f[R]
Gain applied to the output file in dB (default: 0.0).
Does not affect the decoding itself.
.TP
\f[B]/TG\f[R]:\f[I]n\f[R]
Gain applied internally to change the threshold voltage for noise
reduction, in dB (default: 0.0).
Adjusting this is generally preferable to adjusting /IG, as it does not
change the output level.
.SS Output format
.TP
\f[B]/OB\f[R]:\f[I]n\f[R]
Override output bit depth to 8, 16, or 24 bit.
If not specified, the output bit depth matches the input file.
.SS Partial decode
.TP
\f[B]/ST\f[R]:\f[I]n\f[R]
Start of decode section, in seconds.
Allows selecting a subsection of the file to decode faster and avoid
RIFF 64 format.
.TP
\f[B]/LN\f[R]:\f[I]n\f[R]
Length of decode section, in seconds.
Note: the first few moments of the selected section may not be decoded
correctly, as it takes time for the gain control circuits to stabilise.
.SS Decode accuracy and performance
.TP
\f[B]/DA\f[R]:\f[I]n\f[R]
Accuracy of decode, in dB (default: -5.0).
A value of 0.0 means about 1 sample value accuracy.
Higher values decode faster but less accurately; lower values are more
accurate but slower.
.TP
\f[B]/US\f[R]:\f[I]n\f[R]
Upsample rate (default: 0, meaning automatic).
When set to 0, the upsample rate is chosen so that the upper sample rate
is at least 200 kHz.
For example, with 44.1 kHz input, /US defaults to 5 (5 × 44.1 = 220.5
kHz).
Use /US:1 to disable upsampling.
.TP
\f[B]/IB\f[R]:\f[I]n\f[R]
Input buffer size in MB (default: 0, unlimited).
By default, the entire wave file is read into memory before processing.
Use this option to limit the buffer size when memory is insufficient.
.TP
\f[B]/FM\f[R]:\f[I]n\f[R]
Filtering mode for the side path (default: 4).
Four modes are available: 1 is the original method; 2 is a newer method
that generally works better than 1; 3 is an alternative rearrangement
similar to 1; 4 gives the best results in practice.
.SS Verbosity
.TP
\f[B]/S\f[R]:\f[I]n\f[R]
Silent mode.
Use /S:1 for reduced output, /S:2 for minimal output.
.SS RIFF 64 format
.TP
\f[B]/NO64\f[R]
Never use RIFF 64 format.
If the output would exceed the standard WAV size limit, the end of the
file is truncated instead.
.TP
\f[B]/USE64\f[R]
Always use RIFF 64 format, regardless of output size.
.PP
By default, RIFF 64 is used only when the output file would otherwise
exceed the standard WAV size limit.
Not all media players support RIFF 64.
.SS Encode mode
.TP
\f[B]/ENC\f[R]
Run a Dolby B encode instead of a decode.
.SS Miscellaneous
.TP
\f[B]/ALL-HIGH\f[R]
Upsample audio throughout the entire program, not only when required.
This significantly slows processing with no observed improvement in
results.
.TP
\f[B]/RETRY\f[R]
If the input file cannot be opened, wait approximately one second and
try again instead of exiting with an error.
.TP
\f[B]/NOWARN\f[R]
Normally the program pauses at the end if warnings were issued.
This option disables that pause.
.TP
\f[B]/NR-Off\f[R]
Turn off all noise reduction.
Mostly useful for calibration.
.TP
--help
Display help for the command.
.SS Calibration
.TP
\f[B]/CAL\f[R]
Run a calibration process.
Most users do not need this, as the default calibration values are
already built into the program code.
If a recalibration is needed (e.g.\ after changing a parameter file),
this option makes the process more automatic.
Results can be saved with /PE:<filename>.
Calibration with a valid input wave file uses the file\[cq]s sample
rate; without one, /CF:n sets the rate.
.TP
\f[B]/CF\f[R]:\f[I]n\f[R]
Sample rate for calibration (default: 44100).
Used with /CAL when no valid input wave file is provided.
.SS Parameter files
.TP
\f[B]/PF\f[R]:\f[I]<filename>\f[R]
Read program parameters from the specified file.
Intended for advanced users who wish to experiment with internal program
settings.
.TP
\f[B]/PE\f[R]:\f[I]<filename>\f[R]
Create an example parameter file based on current settings.
Options at their default values are included but commented out using
curly brackets.
The file can then be edited and read back in with /PF.
.SH LEVEL ADJUSTMENT
.PP
Dolby B noise reduction is normally applied inside a tape deck where the
audio level is approximately correct.
When using this program, the audio must have already been extracted and
digitised, and no automatic level detection is possible.
.PP
The recommended approach is to decode the same sample section at several
threshold values, compare the results, and then refine the search:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
dolbybi Test.wav Out00.wav /tg:0.0
dolbybi Test.wav Out05.wav /tg:5.0
dolbybi Test.wav Out10.wav /tg:10.0
dolbybi Test.wav Out15.wav /tg:15.0
dolbybi Test.wav Out20.wav /tg:20.0
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Prefer adjusting \f[B]/TG\f[R] (threshold gain) over \f[B]/IG\f[R]
(input gain), because /TG does not change the output level, making it
easier to compare outputs.
In practice, a threshold difference of about 1 dB is audible.
.PP
If the output sounds muffled, especially on quiet parts and transients,
the threshold may be set too low.
If the sound is scratchy or has excessive treble on quiet parts and
transients, the threshold may be set too high.
.PP
Negative threshold and gain values are accepted but are rarely needed.
.SH MULTITHREADING
.PP
The program does not use multithreading internally, but multiple
instances can run in parallel (one per CPU core) to process several
threshold values at the same time.
On Linux:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
dolbybi Test.wav Out00.wav /tg:0.0 &
dolbybi Test.wav Out05.wav /tg:5.0 &
dolbybi Test.wav Out10.wav /tg:10.0 &
wait
\f[R]
.fi
.SH SUPPORTED WAVE FORMATS
.PP
Only WAV type 1 is supported (multi-channel type 2 is not supported).
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Channels\f[R]: 1 (mono) or 2 (stereo)
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Bit depth\f[R]: 8, 16, or 24 bit (other depths are rounded up to
the nearest supported value)
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Sample rate\f[R]: 8000 to 4000000 Hz (all testing was done at 44100
Hz)
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Sample encoding\f[R]: linear PCM only
.PP
Floating point and higher bit depth WAV files are not supported.
Output files are in the same format as the input unless modified by
\f[B]/OB\f[R], \f[B]/ST\f[R], or \f[B]/LN\f[R].
.SH PARAMETER ENTRY
.PP
Command-line parameters are case-insensitive: \f[B]/IG:1.1\f[R] and
\f[B]/Ig:1.1\f[R] are equivalent.
Real values may include a decimal point or be entered as integers.
Negative values are prefixed with a minus sign,
e.g.\ \f[B]/OG:-1.1\f[R].
.SH BUGS
.PP
No known bugs.
.SH SEE ALSO
.PP
